    // where the increasing prefix and decreasing suffix can meet.
    // Any `k` in `[right_reach, left_reach]` can be a peak.
    // For such a `k`, `a[k]` can be made `k` (from left perspective) and `a[k]` can be made `n-1-k` (from right perspective).
    // Since we can decrease elements, we can make `a[k]` equal to `max(k, n-1-k)` or any value larger than its neighbors.
    // The crucial part is that `a[k]` must be strictly greater than `a[k-1]` and `a[k+1]`.
    // If `left_reach >= right_reach`, it means there is at least one index `k`
    // such that `a[k]` can be made `k` (from left) AND `a[k]` can be made `n-1-k` (from right).
    // For example, if `k = left_reach`, then `a[0]...a[left_reach]` can be `0...left_reach`.
    // If `left_reach >= right_reach`, then `left_reach` is also `>= right_reach`.
    // This means `a[left_reach]...a[n-1]` can be `(n-1-left_reach)...0`.
    // So, `a[left_reach]` can be `left_reach` and `a[left_reach]` can be `n-1-left_reach`.
    // Since we can decrease, we can make `a[left_reach]` some value `X` such that `X > left_reach-1` and `X > n-1-(left_reach+1)`.
    // The minimum value `a[left_reach]` can take is `max(left_reach, n-1-left_reach)`.
    // As long as `left_reach >= right_reach`, there is an index `k` that can serve as the peak.
    // For example, `k = right_reach`. `a[0]...a[right_reach]` can be `0...right_reach`.
    // And `a[right_reach]...a[n-1]` can be `(n-1-right_reach)...0`.
    // So, `a[right_reach]` can be `right_reach` and `a[right_reach]` can be `n-1-right_reach`.
    // Both conditions are met for `a[right_reach]`.
    // The peak `k` can be any index `i` such that `i <= left_reach` and `i >= right_reach`.
    // Such an `i` exists if and only if `left_reach >= right_reach`.

    if (left_reach >= right_reach) {
        std::cout << "Yes\n";
    } else {
        std::cout << "No\n";
    }
}

