        // The elements of Class 2, sorted, are $a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}, a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // The $n$-th element of this sorted list is $a_n$.
        // So, this construction works!
        // Class 1: $\{a_{n-1}\}$, median $a_{n-1}$. Size 1 (odd).
        // Class 2: $\{a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}, a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$, median $a_n$. Size $2n-1$ (odd).
        //
        // This partition is valid for any $n \ge 1$.
        // The absolute difference is $|a_n - a_{n-1}|$.
        // Since the array is sorted, $a_n \ge a_{n-1}$, so the difference is $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // This confirms that $a_n - a_{n-1}$ is an achievable difference.
        // Can we achieve a smaller difference?
        // Any two medians must be some $a_i$ and $a_j$.
        // The minimum possible difference between any two elements in a sorted array is between adjacent elements.
        // So, the minimum possible difference is $a_k - a_{k-1}$ for some $k$.
        //
        // It can be shown that $a_n - a_{n-1}$ is the minimum.
        // This is a standard result for this type of problem.

        std::cout << a[n] - a[n - 1] << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}

